Use `Dali::Animation::FinishedSignal` when app logic must run after an animation completes. The signal callback receives the completed `Dali::Animation`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

class Controller : public ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void PlayDismiss(View view)
  {
    Animation animation = Animation::New(0.2f);

    view.Animate(animation)
      .Opacity(0.0f, Duration(0.2f));

    animation.FinishedSignal().Connect(this, &Controller::OnDismissFinished);
    animation.Play();
  }

private:
  void OnDismissFinished(Animation animation)
  {
    animation.Clear();
  }
};
```

## Property Ownership

In dali-ui application code, prefer typed `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationBridge` and `Dali::Ui::ViewAnimationSpec` calls instead of manually addressing properties. The app-facing object remains `Dali::Ui::View`.

Some animated values are inherited transform or opacity properties. When those properties are discussed by enum owner, the typed view animation calls map to `Dali::Actor::Property` values such as `Dali::Actor::Property::OPACITY`, `Dali::Actor::Property::POSITION_X`, `Dali::Actor::Property::POSITION_Y`, `Dali::Actor::Property::SCALE_X`, and `Dali::Actor::Property::SCALE_Y`. The dali-ui bridge hides the low-level property wiring while still animating the view.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

void ShowAsSelected(View view)
{
  Animation animation = Animation::New(0.3f);

  view.Animate(animation)
    .Opacity(1.0f, Duration(0.3f))
    .ScaleX(1.05f, Duration(0.3f))
    .ScaleY(1.05f, Duration(0.3f));

  animation.SetEndAction(Animation::BAKE);
  animation.Play();
}
```

